    <h2>How to complete this workbook</h2>

    <p>Under CEQR, an air quality assessment of mobile and stationary sources determines both a proposed project's effects on ambient air quality, as well as the effects of ambient air quality on the project. This page provides a download of permit information for Light Industrial, Large, and Major stationary source facilities in order to assess potential effects on the ambient air quality surrounding the proposed project, as part of a preliminary stationary source screening.</p>
    <br>
    <p>DEP Clean Air Tracking System (CATS) Light Industrial Process Permit records, NYS State Air Facility Permit records, and NYS Title V Air Permit record data can be used to allocate Light Industrial, Large, and Major sources within the study area (using the radiuses specified in the CEQR Technical Manual) to determine whether detailed analyses for air toxic emissions are required.</p>

    <h2>How can I find related permit records using this data?</h2>

    <h3>Identify permits using shapefiles</h3>

    <p>Downloadable shapefiles for each data set include locations of the air emission sources, importing the shapefiles into mapping softwares, e.g. ArcGIS, helps to allocate the sources within the study area.</p>

    <p>Per CEQR Technical Manual, Light Industrial source should be analyzed within 400 feet radius from the project site; Large and Major sources should be analyzed within 1000 feet radius from the project site.</p>

    <h3>Request permit records</h3>

    <p>For access to DEP CATS Light Industrial Permits, please request a "DEP Air Permit Request" form by contacting DEPâ€™S Bureau of Environmental Compliance at <a href="mailto:airpermit@dep.nyc.gov">airpermit@dep.nyc.gov</a>. For NYS DEC State Facility Air Permits and Title V Air Permits, direct permit download can be accessed through the url link provided in the shapefiles and the Excel files.</p>

